---
<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="Sesame Oil Guide" description="Sesame oil — toasted vs light, when to add it, Asian cooking essential." canonical="https://28grams.vip/sesame-oil-guide" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>Sesame Oil Guide</h1><p>An essential ingredient in Asian cuisine.</p></div>

    <h2>Toasted vs Light</h2>
    <p>Toasted sesame oil is dark, highly aromatic, and boasts a rich, nutty flavor. Light (or untoasted) sesame oil is pale and has a much milder taste, suitable for general cooking.</p>
    <h2>When to Add It</h2>
    <p>Because toasted sesame oil has a lower smoke point and its delicate flavor can degrade under high heat, it is typically added at the end of cooking as a finishing oil or used in cold dressings.</p>
    <h2>An Asian Cooking Essential</h2>
    <p>It provides the signature flavor profile in many marinades, stir-fries, and dipping sauces across various Asian cuisines.</p>
